findings.recommendation:
Before calling CheckIOAvailable, validate that the PID obtained from pg_stat_activity is > 0 and < /proc/sys/kernel/pid_max (or use a conservative upper bound such as 4194304). Add an explicit pid > 0 guard inside CheckIOAvailable itself as a defence-in-depth measure, matching the pattern already in readProcPidStat/readProcPidIO. Example guard in CheckIOAvailable:

  if pid <= 0 {
    return fmt.Errorf("invalid pid: %d", pid)
  }

In app.setup(), after parsing the PID from the query result:

  if pid <= 0 || pid > 4194304 {
    // skip probe, ioAvailable = false
  }

Add a maximum size check before reading sysinfo entries. Given that SysInfo has only two numeric fields, 512 bytes is a generous upper bound:

  const maxSysinfoSize = 512
  if strings.HasPrefix(hdr.Name, "sysinfo.") {
    if hdr.Size > maxSysinfoSize {
      return fmt.Errorf("sysinfo entry too large: %d bytes", hdr.Size)
    }
    // decode...
  }

This mirrors the bounded read already used in CheckDelayAcctAvailable.

Emit a one-time INFO log when ioAvailable was true at setup but every PID read returns EACCES during the first collect() tick. A simple counter approach:

  // After the PID loop in collect()
  if c.config.ioAvailable && ioSuccessCount == 0 && len(pids) > 0 {
    fmt.Println("INFO: /proc/[pid]/io not readable — IO columns will be empty")
  }
